n": {"begin": 413, "end": 417}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:29832"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "S", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.999553382396698, "span": {"begin": 422, "end": 423}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:30158"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "BH4", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9986287355422974, "span": {"begin": 460, "end": 463}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4846"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "eNOS", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9920929074287415, "span": {"begin": 473, "end": 477}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013481"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "superoxide", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9997116923332214, "span": {"begin": 497, "end": 507}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:54890"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "oxygenase domain", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.8957507610321045, "span": {"begin": 560, "end": 576}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013481"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "superoxide", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9997625946998596, "span": {"begin": 581, "end": 591}}, {"id": ["mesh:D019331"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "L-NG-nitroarginine methyl ester", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9992308020591736, "span": {"begin": 626, "end": 657}}, {"id": ["mesh:D019331"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "L-NAME", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9992800951004028, "span": {"begin": 659, "end": 665}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:29832"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "S", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9995748400688171, "span": {"begin": 684, "end": 685}}, {"id": ["mesh:D002118"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "calcium", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9994730353355408, "span": {"begin": 726, "end": 733}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:808", "805"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "calmodulin", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9724825620651245, "span": {"begin": 734, "end": 744}}, {"id": ["mesh:D006418"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "heme", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.952989935874939, "span": {"begin": 749, "end": 753}}], "text": "Oxidative stress can trigger S-glutathionylation of eNOS at cysteine residues Cys689 and Cys908, which are known to be critical for normal eNOS function (Zweier et al., 2011). S-glutathionylation directly causes eNOS uncoupling, a state in which eNOS switches from producing NO to generating superoxide, thus impairing endothelium-dependent vasodilation and contributing to endothelial dysfunction. Uncoupling of eNOS via S-glutathionylation is different from BH4-mediated eNOS uncoupling in that superoxide is produced in the reductase domain rather than the oxygenase domain and superoxide generation cannot be inhibited by L-NG-nitroarginine methyl ester (L-NAME), suggesting that S-glutathionylation occurs independent of calcium/calmodulin and heme.", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:52:27 +0000 2026"}